<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1440,1763,1851]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,387,1763,1787]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Relationships.</emphasis>
In its decurved, relatively short ovipositor and strongly expanded postpetiole this species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Porter 1967)" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[321,614,1795,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Phycitiplex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charieis">
<emphasis box="[321,449,1795,1819]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">P. charieis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, C. C." box="[462,607,1795,1819]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" refId="ref6744" refString="Porter, C. C. 1967. A Revision of the South American Species of Trachysphyrus (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae). Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 10: 368 p." type="book" year="1967">Porter 1967</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from which it differs by having a complete subapical white band and shallow but well defined punctures on the second gastric tergite.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5170159" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5170159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5170159/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" startId="10.[194,278,1161,1183]" targetBox="[192,1441,194,1134]" targetPageId="10">
